{"cursor":"52076","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n]] The 'fire services in the United Kingdom' operate under separate legislative\nand administrative arrangements in England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and\nWales. Fire services have undergone significant changes since the beginning of\nthe 21st century, a process that has been propelled by a devolution of central\ngovernment powers, new legislation and a change to operational procedures in the\nlight of terrorism attacks and threats. The catalyst for change came with the\n2002 publication of a review of the fire service in the United Kingdom by\nProfessor Sir George Bain. His report, the Independent Review of the Fire\nService, led to rapid changes to fire and rescue services. Bain's terms of\nreference were described as follows: \"Having regard to the changing and\ndeveloping role of the Fire Service in the United Kingdom, to inquire into and\nmake recommendations on the future organisation and management of the Fire\nService...\" [http://www.frsonline.fire.gov.uk/publications/article/17/306 FRS\nOnline (accessed 02 Sep 07) links to full report PDF: Independent Review of the\nFire Service pub Dec 2002] In the foreword to the review, Bain stated that\nit was carried out independently and objectively: \"...the Review was put\ntogether with the co-operation of the Government, the employers' organisations\nand fire authorities in England and Wales, Scotland and Northern\nIreland.\" [http://www.frsonline.fire.gov.uk/publications/article/17/306 FRS\nOnline (accessed 02 Sep 07) links to full report PDF: Independent Review of the\nFire Service: foreword page: i]\n","linknr":911,"url":"Fire_service_in_the_United_Kingdom","recorded":1362570622,"links":33,"instances":["united_kingdom","council_area","council_area","council_area","westminster_system","united_kingdom","scotland_act_2005","county_borough","council_area","emergency_telephone_number","county_borough","county_borough","county_borough","fire_saf